1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. g3 a5
9. Nh2 Na6 10. Be2 Nf6 11. Ng4 Nc5 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. h4 Qe7 14. h5 gxh5 15.
Be3 f5 {All book up to this now. Here Holt, who was habitually late for the
game, relied on his memory and quickly played} 16. Rxh5 ({There are three
games of GM Lysyj indicating that} 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. Rxh5 Ra6 18. Qd3 f4 {is
the proper way to get to the key position.}) 16... f4 {Becerra took quite a
bit of time on this one, but I don\'t think his move was correct} (16... Nxe4 $1
{is what Lysyj tried to avoid. After} 17. Nxe4 fxe4 18. Qc2 Bf5 {White is
practically forced to sac the exchange,} 19. Rxf5 $5 ({if not, then Black
would do it himself!} 19. O-O-O Bg6 20. Rhh1 Rxf2 $1 21. Bxf2 e3 22. Bd3 e4 $15
) 19... Rxf5 20. Qxe4 {but then Black\'s superior development would keep him
out of trouble:} Raf8 21. Bg4 R5f6 {White has two ways of getting his exchange
back, Bg5 and Be6+, but neither one is good enough to equalize the game.
Otherwise,} 22. O-O-O $140 Bh6) 17. Bxc5 dxc5 18. Qd3 $2 {This is a good
example of what some call "mechanical play". The same queen move was played
with the black pawn still on f5, and now Holt plays it without thinking.} ({
Look what he missed - an easy to find positionally superior move} 18. Bg4)
18... Qf7 {White\'s opening advantage is gone.} 19. gxf4 $2 {And now he\'s going
to be worse.} (19. Rh2 $142) 19... Qxf4 20. Qe3 Ra6 21. Qxf4 Rxf4 $15 22. Rd1
Bd7 23. Rd3 Be8 24. Rg5 Rh6 25. Bf3 Bg6 26. Ne2 Rf7 27. Ng3 Kf8 28. Ke2 Bf6 29.
Rg4 Be7 30. Rd1 Rf6 31. Rd3 Rh3 32. Nf1 h5 33. Rg2 Kf7 34. Rb3 b6 35. Re3 Bf8
36. Ng3 Bh6 37. Rc3 Bf4 38. Nf5 Rxf5 (38... Bxf5 39. exf5 Rh4 40. Rd3 Rxf5 41.
d6) 39. Rxg6 (39. exf5 Bxf5 40. Rg1 e4 41. Bxe4 (41. Bg2 Rh2) 41... Rxc3 42.
Bxf5 Rxc4 $15) 39... Kxg6 40. exf5+ Kg5 41. Be4 $2 (41. Rd3 Bc1 42. d6 cxd6 43.
Rxd6) 41... Rxc3 42. bxc3 h4 (42... a4 {would not change much. White holds the
draw after} 43. a3 Bc1 44. Bc2 Bxa3 45. Bxa4 Kxf5 46. Kf3 Bb2 47. Bd7+ Kg5 48.
Ke4 Bxc3 49. Bc8 Be1 50. Kxe5 Bxf2 51. Ke4 b5 52. cxb5 c4 53. Be6 c3 54. Kd3
Bd4 55. d6 $1 cxd6 56. Bb3) 43. Bg2 Kxf5 44. Bh3+ Kg5 45. Kd3 Bc1 46. Ke4 Kf6
47. a4 Bd2 48. d6 $2 {This unnecessary pawn sac cost Holt the game and
advanced Miami into the semifinals.} (48. Bd7 Bxc3 49. f3 Bd2 50. Kd3 Be1 51.
Ke4 Bf2 52. Kd3 {In this key position Black has to decide where to move the
king.} Ke7 {looks more promising. Still, after} (52... Kg5 53. Ke4 b5 54. axb5
$1 {White can handle the a-pawn. It\'s important to keep his own counterplay.} (
54. cxb5 $2 c4 55. Bh3 c3 56. Kd3 Kf4 {is hopelessly lost.}) 54... a4 55. d6
cxd6 56. b6 d5+ 57. cxd5 (57. Kxd5 a3 58. b7 a2 59. b8=Q a1=Q 60. Qxe5+) 57...
c4 58. b7 Ba7 59. d6 Bb8 60. Bxa4 Bxd6 61. Bd7 $11) 53. Bh3 Kd6 54. Ke4 (54.
Be6 c6) (54. Bg4 Bd4 55. Bh3 b5 56. axb5 a4) 54... b5 55. axb5 a4 56. Kd3 Bd4
57. Kc2 e4 58. fxe4 Be5 59. Kb1 Bf4 60. Ka2 Ke5 61. Ka3 Kd4 62. Bf1 $1 ({not} 
62. Be6 Kxc4 63. d6+ Kxb5) 62... Kxe4 63. Kxa4 {White breaks through on the
queenside and holds an easy draw.} Ke3 64. b6 cxb6 65. Kb5 Kf2 66. Bh3 Kg3 67.
Be6 h3 68. Bxh3 Kxh3 69. Kxb6 $11) 48... cxd6 49. Kd5 Kg5 50. Ke4 Bxc3 51. Be6
Be1 52. f3 Bd2 53. Kd3 (53. Bd7 Bb4 {The ideal spot for the bishop.} 54. Be6
d5+ 55. Bxd5 (55. Kxe5 Bc3+ 56. Kxd5 Kf4 57. Kc6 Kxf3 58. Kxb6 Bb4) (55. cxd5
c4 56. d6 Bxd6 57. Bxc4 h3) 55... h3 56. Kxe5 Bc3+ 57. Ke4 h2 58. f4+ Kg4 59.
Ke3 Bd4+ 60. Ke2 Kxf4 61. Kf1 Ke3 62. Kg2 Kd3 63. Kxh2 b5 $19) 53... Kf4 $1 {
The easiest way to win - Black has too many pawns for White to contain.} 54.
Kxd2 Kxf3 55. Bd7 Ke4 56. Bh3 Kd4 57. Be6 h3 58. Bxh3 Kxc4 59. Bd7 Kd4 60. Bg4
c4 61. Be6 d5 62. Bf7 Kc5 63. Ke3 d4+ 64. Ke4 d3 65. Ke3 b5 66. axb5 Kxb5 67.
Bd5 Kb4 68. Kd2 a4 69. Kc1 Kc3 70. Kb1 Kd4 71. Bc6 a3 72. Ka2 e4 0-1
