1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 {Due to the difficulties White
experiences in both the Berlin and the Marshall, this modest pawn move has
become the main line of the 21st Century Ruy Lopez.} d6 6. c3 g6 {It is
natural for a Kings Indian specialist, such as Julio Becerra , to fianchetto
his king bishop when opportunity presents itself.} 7. O-O ({An interesting
plan was introduced by GM Stripunsky:} 7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. Nf1 O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4
Bd7 11. Ne3 {and somewhat surprisingly he answered} Qc8 {with} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6
13. h4 $1 {This well illustrates a great variety of ideas present in modern
chess.}) 7... Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 Bd7 10. Nbd2 ({White can play} 10. d4 {
that\'s for sure, but GM Becerra had faced it before:} Re8 ({Super GM
Mamedyarov\'s} 10... h6 {may be considerd an improvement, as Black wants to
avoid moving his king rook back and forth.}) 11. d5 Ne7 12. Bc2 Rf8 {Despite
the time lost on the rook moves GM Becerra feels comfortable in a familiar
settings of the Kings Indian Defense.} 13. c4 Ne8 14. Nc3 h6 15. b4 f5 16. c5
f4) 10... Qe8 11. Bc2 (11. Nf1 Nh5 12. Bb3 Kh8 13. d4 f5 {is very complicated.
Such lines attract attention of many strong young players of today.}) 11... Nh5
12. Nf1 f5 13. Ne3 fxe4 ({One may wonder why Becerra passed on a chance to
grab himself some kingsiode space with a standard pawn push. The thing is,
after} 13... f4 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. d4 {there\'s too much tension in the center for
Black to be able to focus on g5-g4.}) 14. dxe4 Kh8 15. Nd5 Rc8 16. Be3 Nd8 17.
c4 $6 {This is one of those moves that are so obvious even great players play
them without thinking. In retrospect, Matikozyan should have avoided weakening
the d4-square, but who could predict Black\'s 18th move?} Ne6 18. b4 c5 $3 {It
weakens everything: the d6-pawn, the d5-square and makes a hole on b6, but all
things considered, it\'s a great move! It\'s all about the d4-square.} 19. bxc5 (
19. Rb1 Bc6) 19... dxc5 20. a4 Nd4 $13 21. Nh2 Qf7 22. a5 Rce8 23. Qd2 Bc6 24.
Ra3 Nf6 {Becerra chooses to maintain the tension.} ({In case of the plausible} 
24... Nf4 25. Bxf4 exf4 26. Nf3 {White would have a easier task.}) 25. Bd3 Re6
26. Rb1 Ne8 27. Ra2 Nd6 28. Qc1 Rc8 29. Nb6 Rd8 30. Nd5 Ree8 31. Qa3 {
Matikozyan found a weaknwss in Black\'s camp - the pawn on c5, but his major
pieces have dangerously drifted away from the kingside.} Bxd5 32. exd5 e4 $1
33. Bf1 (33. Qxc5 Rc8 34. Qxd6 exd3 {would give Black plenty of play.}) 33...
Rc8 34. Rb6 N6f5 35. Qc1 (35. Rab2 Nxe3 (35... Re7) 36. fxe3 Nf5 37. Rxb7 Rc7
38. Rxc7 Qxc7 {White is up a pawn, and it\'s a good one, but his king is
terribly weak on the dark squares.}) 35... Re7 36. Be2 h5 37. Nf1 Rf8 38. Bd1
Nxe3 39. Nxe3 Nf5 40. Nxf5 Qxf5 41. g4 Qf7 42. Rb3 h4 ({Becerra had} 42... e3
43. Rxe3 Qf4 44. Qa3 Be5 45. Qxc5 Qh2+ 46. Kf1 Ref7 {which would likely force
White to part with his queen,} 47. Rxe5 Qh1+ 48. Ke2 Rxf2+ 49. Qxf2 Rxf2+ 50.
Kxf2 Qh2+ 51. Kf1 Qxe5 {Not sure Black can win this one.}) 43. Qg5 Kg8 44. Rb6
$2 {A logical attempt to counterattack, but it falls to a wicked tactic.} (44.
d6 Re5 (44... Re6 45. Qd5) 45. Qe3 {was the only way to continue.}) 44... e3
45. f3 (45. f4 $5) 45... e2 $19 (45... Bf6 46. Qh6 Qg7 $11) 46. Bxe2 (46. Rxe2
Qxf3) 46... Rxe2 47. Rxe2 Qxf3 {Black\'s attack is unstoppable.} 48. Rg2 Qd1+
49. Kh2 Rf1 50. Qd8+ Bf8 51. Qxh4 (51. Rxg6+ Kf7 52. Qd7+ Kxg6 53. Qe6+ Kh7 54.
Qe4+ Kh8 55. Qe5+ Bg7 56. Qe8+ Rf8 {and the checks have run out.}) 51... Rh1+
52. Kg3 Qd3+ 53. Kf4 Qd4+ 54. Kf3 Qd3+ 55. Kf4 Qd4+ (55... Rf1+ 56. Rf2 Re1) (
55... Qxc4+ 56. Ke5 Qc3+ 57. Ke6 Re1+ 58. Kd7 Qg7+ 59. Kc8 Re8+) 56. Kf3 Rxh3+
57. Qxh3 Qd3+ 58. Kf2 Qxh3 59. Rxg6+ Bg7 60. Rg3 Qh2+ 61. Kf3 Kf7 62. Re6 Bd4
63. Re2 Qh1+ 64. Rgg2 Qh7 65. Kg3 Qd3+ 66. Kh2 Qxc4 67. g5 Qxd5 68. g6+ Kf8 0-1[White "Anka-SEA"]
[Black "Bartell-PHI"]
[Result "0-1"]

