1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 e6 ({The
theoretically approved line} 7... Nb6 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. e6+ Kg8 10. d5 {scares
me.}) 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Qe4 {White\'s play is all about the space
provided by the e5-pawn and the developing kingside attack.} Bd7 11. Re1 $1 {
It\'s important not to rush your threats.} ({The automatic} 11. Bd3 $6 {is
adequatly answered with} f5 12. exf6 Nxf6) 11... Rc8 12. a3 $1 {Eric
demonstrates his knowledge of opening subtleties.} (12. Nbd2 {allows Black to
unroll his counterplay:} b5 13. Bb3 (13. Bxb5 Nxe5) 13... Na5 14. Bc2 f5 15.
exf6 Nxf6 16. Qd3 Qc7 {etc}) 12... Qc7 ({The computer suggested} 12... Na5 13.
Ba2 Ba4 14. Qg4 Bc2 {looks attractive, as the bishop comes to defend the king}
{but White has the energetic} 15. Bxd5 (15. Nbd2 Bf5 16. Qg3 b5 17. Ne4) 15...
exd5 16. Nc3 Nb3 17. Nxd5 $1 {threatening Qxc8.}) (12... Qb6 {was played in
Nepo-Vachier when they were stars of the World Youth Chess.}) ({I\'d also look
at} 12... b5 13. Ba2 (13. Bxd5 exd5 14. Qxd5 Na5 15. exd6 Bc6 16. Qf5 Bxd6 17.
Ng5 g6 18. Qh3 h5) 13... b4) 13. Nbd2 Rfd8 14. Ba2 Na5 15. Qg4 dxe5 16. dxe5
Qc2 {It seemed Black was doing alright, but the continuation of the game
turned out anything but safe.} (16... h5 17. Qxh5 (17. Qg3 $142) 17... Nf4 18.
Qg4 Nd3) 17. Ne4 Nb3 18. Bh6 g6 (18... Bf8 19. Bxb3 Qxb3 20. Nf6+) 19. Bxb3
Qxb3 20. Bg5 {White assumes control over the dark squares.} Bxg5 21. Nfxg5 (21.
Qxg5 $16) 21... h6 22. Qh4 $3 hxg5 23. Nxg5 Be8 24. Rad1 Rc4 (24... Qxb2 25.
Rb1 (25. Qh6 Rc2) 25... Qc3 26. Qh7+ Kf8 27. Qh8+ Ke7 28. Ne4 Qc6 29. Qh4+ Kd7
30. Nd6 Kc7) 25. Qh6 Qa4 26. b4 $3 Qxa3 27. Nh7 $2 {The only blemish in the
otherwise perfect attacking game.} (27. Rxd5 exd5 (27... Rxd5 28. Nh7) 28. e6)
27... Qxb4 $2 ({Irina missed the only defense:} 27... Qc3 28. h3 f5 29. Re3 {
and then there\'s another pitfall to avoid:} Nxe3 $2 30. Nf6+ Kf7 31. Qh7+ Kf8
32. Qg8+ Ke7 33. Rd7+ $3 {mates.}) 28. Nf6+ Nxf6 29. exf6 Qf8 30. Qxf8+ Kxf8
31. Rxd8 Rf4 32. Rc1 1-0
