1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. e4 {Holt is a big expert in this
line having played it a dozen of times, icncluding an important game against
GM Onischuk in this year\'s U.S. Championship.} d5 6. e5 Ne4 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nf3
cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nd7 10. Bf4 Qh4 11. g3 Qh3 12. O-O-O Nxc3 13. bxc3 Ba3+ 14. Kb1
Nb6 15. Bf1 Qh5 16. Be2 Qg6 ({In case of} 16... Qh3 {White may consider} 17.
cxd5 Nxd5 (17... exd5 18. f3 {still going after the black queen.}) 18. Bd2 Bc5
19. Qe4 {threatening Bg4 and threfore forcing} f5) 17. Bd3 Qh5 18. Be2 Qg6 19.
Bd3 (19. Be3 Be7 20. Qxg6 hxg6 21. Nb5 Bd7 {Didn\'t bring White much success in
Khalifman-Alekseev}) 19... Qh5 {Some games ended right here in move repetition,
but Holt has ambitions.} 20. g4 $3 Qxg4 21. Qd2 Nxc4 {It is logical to both
exchange White\'s attacking bishop and double up you material advantage all in
one move.} ({Besides,} 21... Qh3 {doesn\'t look much better:} 22. Rhg1 g6 23.
Rg3 Qh5 24. Be2 Qh4 25. Bg5 Qe4+ 26. Nc2 Bc5 27. Bf6) 22. Bxc4 dxc4 23. Rhg1
Qh4 $2 {An unfortunate decision that gives the white bishop a key tempo.} ({
Meanwhile,} 23... Qh3 24. Bh6 g6 25. Nb5 Be7 26. Bxf8 Kxf8 27. Nd6 Bd7 28. Qf4
Be8 {is playable for both sides.}) 24. Bg5 Qh5 25. Bf6 g6 26. f3 $1 {IM Schoer
must have missed this shot.} Re8 ({Holt\'s idea would become reality in case of
} 26... Bd7 27. Rg4 Ba4 28. Rh4) 27. Rg5 $1 {White demonstrates great tactical
skills.} ({Apparently, Holt wasn\'t satisfied with} 27. Rg4 Be7 28. Rh4 Qxh4 29.
Bxh4 Bxh4 30. Qf4 Bd8 31. Nb5 {although Whiter looks much better/near winning
here.}) 27... Qh6 28. Nb5 $1 {Holt finds a way to take advantage of Re8.} Qf8
29. Nc7 Rb8 30. Nxe8 {It is already over.} b5 (30... Qxe8 31. Qd8) 31. Qd8 b4
32. Qd6 Bb7 33. Qxb8 Bxf3 34. Bg7 Qc5 35. Bh6 Be4+ 36. Ka1 Bb2+ 37. Kxb2 bxc3+
38. Ka1 1-0
