1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bf5 6. g3 e6 7. Bg2 Nbd7 8.
Nc3 Be7 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Nd2 O-O 11. Nc4 Qa6 12. e4 Bg6 13. Bg5 Rfe8 14. e5 {
White enjoys some spatial advantage provided by the e5-pawn, but he hasn\'t
castled yet.} Bd3 {Nice rejoinder.} ({Although the simple} 14... Nd5 15. Bxe7
Rxe7 16. Nd6 f6 {was playable as well as the text.}) 15. Bf1 Bxf1 16. Rxf1 Ng4
{This seems like a very bad move until you see the follow-up} (16... Nd5 17.
Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Ne4 c5 $1 $36 {Once again illustrates the importance of king
safety.}) 17. Bxe7 Nxh2 $5 {An incredible idea from GM Finegold.} ({Now} 17...
Rxe7 18. f3 Nh6 19. g4 c5 20. Rd1 {favors White because of the bad position of
Nh6.}) 18. O-O-O ({I was wondering about} 18. Bc5 {until I found out that a
piece sacrifice} Nxc5 19. dxc5 Nf3+ 20. Kd1 Rad8+ 21. Kc1 Nxe5 22. Ne3 Rd3 {
gives Black lasting initiative.}) 18... Nxf1 19. Ba3 Nb6 ({An attempt to break
open the  An attempt to break open the queenside} 19... b5 20. Nd6 Reb8 21. Bb4
Qb6 {would fail to the careful} 22. Nce4 a5 23. Bc5 {keeping the hatches
batten.}) 20. Nd6 Nd5 21. Nce4 {I think Margvelashvili tried for more} ({than
the perfectly playable} 21. Nxd5 cxd5 22. Qf3 Re7 23. Qg2 Rc7+ 24. Kb1) 21...
Qe2 22. Qxb7 $1 ({Taking back the exchange would allow Black to save the
queenside pawns.} 22. Nxe8 Rxe8 23. Nd6 Rb8) 22... Rf8 23. Qxc6 a5 {The
purpose of this move was to play Nb4, but Black never got around to doing this.
} (23... Nh2 $142) 24. Qc4 Rfc8 25. Bc5 Qxc4+ 26. Nxc4 Nh2 27. Kd2 Ng4 28. f3
Nh6 29. g4 {White has more than enough for the exchange. On his next move
Finegold begins a risky plan designed to return Nh6 into action.} f5 30. exf6
gxf6 31. g5 fxg5 32. Nxg5 Kg7 $5 {Incredible. The black king just walks into
it, yet there\'s no refutation to Finegold\'s play.} (32... Nf5 33. Nxe6 $14) 33.
Nd6 ({I\'d mention} 33. Re1 Kf6 34. Ne4+ Kg7 35. Ncd6 {as the most attractive
continuation I could find for Whte.}) (33. Nxe6+ Kf6 34. Re1 Nf5 {is exactly
what Ben had in mind.}) 33... Rg8 34. Rh1 Nf4 35. Rh4 Kg6 $1 {Once again, the
king defends himself and attacks opponent\'s pieces - a concept worthy of
Steinitz himself.} 36. Nde4 Ng2 37. Rh2 Nf4 38. Rh4 Ng2 39. Rh2 Nf4 40. Bd6 Nd5
41. Be5 Nf7 42. Nxf7 Kxf7 43. Rxh7+ Kg6 44. Rh1 Raf8 45. Nd6 Rxf3 46. Rg1+ Kh7
47. Rh1+ Kg6 48. Rg1+ Kh7 1/2-1/2
